{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3755978,"name":"Eli Benevedes","username":"MrRoboman4321","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/mrroboman4321/{size}/271120_2.png","created_at":"2025-10-05T20:59:15.292Z","cooked":"<p>This is a follow-on to the question in <a href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/t/wpilib-units-to-convert-rotations-to-distance/506874" class="inline-onebox">WPILib Units to convert Rotations to Distance</a> , but since that was answered I figured I’d create a new thread.</p>
<p>From the previous thread, I have this code:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">public class Constants {
    public static final PerUnit&lt;DistanceUnit, AngleUnit&gt; MetersPerRotation = Meters.per(Rotation);

    private static final double _METERS_PER_ROTATION = 1.0;
    public static final Per&lt;DistanceUnit, AngleUnit&gt; METERS_PER_ROTATION = MetersPerRotation.ofNative(_METERS_PER_ROTATION);
}

public class Elevator {
    // ...

    @Override
    public void updateInputs(ElevatorIOInputs inputs) {
        // ...

        // leftInputs.position is of type Angle, read from a motor. inputs.height is of type Distance
        inputs.height = (Distance) Constants.METERS_PER_ROTATION.timesDivisor(leftInputs.position);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>This works great for updating the height input based on the inputs from my motor subclass. I would like to do the same to convert the motor’s AngularVelocity into a LinearVelocity. The only way I have managed to get the type system to agree is with this:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">public class Constants {
    public static final PerUnit&lt;DistanceUnit, AngleUnit&gt; MetersPerRotation = Meters.per(Rotation);
    public static final PerUnit&lt;LinearVelocityUnit, AngularVelocityUnit&gt; MetersPerSecondPerRotationPerSecond = MetersPerSecond.per(RotationsPerSecond);

    private static final double _METERS_PER_ROTATION = 1.0;
    public static final Per&lt;DistanceUnit, AngleUnit&gt; METERS_PER_ROTATION = MetersPerRotation.ofNative(_METERS_PER_ROTATION);
    public static final Per&lt;LinearVelocityUnit, AngularVelocityUnit&gt; METERS_PER_SECOND_PER_ROTATIONS_PER_SECOND = MetersPerSecondPerRotationPerSecond.ofNative(_METERS_PER_ROTATION);
}

public class Elevator {
    // ...

    @Override
    public void updateInputs(ElevatorIOInputs inputs) {
        // ...

        // leftInputs.position is of type Angle, read from a motor. inputs.height is of type Distance
        inputs.height = (Distance) Constants.METERS_PER_ROTATION.timesDivisor(leftInputs.position);

        // leftInputs.position is of type AngularVelocity. inputs.velocity is of type LinearVelocity.
        inputs.velocity = (LinearVelocity) Constants.METERS_PER_SECOND_PER_ROTATIONS_PER_SECOND.timesDivisor(leftInputs.velocity);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>I have a few problems with this approach:</p>
<ul>
<li>The <code>MetersPerSecondPerRotationsPerSecond</code> type is egregiously explicit</li>
<li>I already have a <code>MetersPerRotation</code> type. There should be a way to more simply do the unit transformation: <code>Meters/Rotation * Rotations/Sec == Meters/Sec</code>. This is equivalent dimensionally to <code>((Meters/Sec) / (Rotations/Sec)) * (Rotations/Sec) == Meters/Sec</code>, but much simpler.</li>
</ul>
<p>Is there a way I can reuse my <code>Constant.METERS_PER_ROTATION</code> conversion factor, and get a value of type <code>MetersPerSecond</code> or <code>LinearVelocity</code> out of it? <code>timesConversionFactor</code> looks the most promising, but the generic type requirements don’t seem to line up with what I’m asking for.</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-10-06T14:48:12.362Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":212,"readers_count":211,"score":57.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":506892,"topic_slug":"wpilib-units-part-2-unit-conversions-and-cancellations","display_username":"Eli Benevedes","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":3,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/t/wpilib-units-to-convert-rotations-to-distance/506874","internal":true,"reflection":false,"title":"WPILib Units to convert Rotations to Distance","clicks":12}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":26423,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"1983 Mentor/Alum"},"post_url":"/t/wpilib-units-part-2-unit-conversions-and-cancellations/506892/1","custom_user_title":"1983 Mentor/Alum","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3756295,"name":"Poppeseed","username":"Poppeseed","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/poppeseed/{size}/167218_2.png","created_at":"2025-10-06T13:45:09.673Z","cooked":"<p>We just resort to using SI units and radians to convert between linear and angular units. I do have concerns on memory usage with creating Unit objects on the fly like this though.</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">public class DistanceAngleConverter
{
    private Distance rollerRadius;

    public static DistanceAngleConverter getDefault()
    {
        return new DistanceAngleConverter(Inches.of(1.0));
    }

    public DistanceAngleConverter(Distance radius)
    {
        this.rollerRadius = radius;
    }

    public Distance getRadius()
    {
        return rollerRadius;
    }

    public Distance toDistance(Angle angle)
    {
        return rollerRadius.times(angle.in(Radians));
    }

    public Angle toAngle(Distance position)
    {
        return Radians.of(position.div(rollerRadius).magnitude());
    }

    public LinearVelocity toLinearVelocity(AngularVelocity angularVelocity)
    {
        return MetersPerSecond.of(angularVelocity.in(RadiansPerSecond) * rollerRadius.in(Meters));
    }

    public AngularVelocity toAngularVelocity(LinearVelocity linearVelocity)
    {
        return RadiansPerSecond.of(linearVelocity.in(MetersPerSecond) / rollerRadius.in(Meters));
    }

    public AngularAcceleration toAngularAcceleration(LinearAcceleration linearAccel)
    {
        return RadiansPerSecondPerSecond.of(linearAccel.in(MetersPerSecondPerSecond) / rollerRadius.in(Meters));
    }

    public LinearAcceleration toLinearAcceleration(AngularAcceleration angularAccel)
    {
        return MetersPerSecondPerSecond.of(angularAccel.in(RadiansPerSecondPerSecond) * rollerRadius.in(Meters));
    }

    public Velocity&lt;AngularAccelerationUnit&gt; toAngularJerk(Velocity&lt;LinearAccelerationUnit&gt; linearJerk)
    {
        return RadiansPerSecondPerSecond.per(Second).of(linearJerk.in(MetersPerSecondPerSecond.per(Second)) / rollerRadius.in(Meters));
    }
}
</code></pre>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-10-06T13:45:09.673Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":117,"readers_count":116,"score":28.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":506892,"topic_slug":"wpilib-units-part-2-unit-conversions-and-cancellations","display_username":"Poppeseed","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":27767,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/wpilib-units-part-2-unit-conversions-and-cancellations/506892/2","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3756360,"name":"Raphael","username":"Raphdf201","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/raphdf201/{size}/271136_2.png","created_at":"2025-10-06T15:52:41.625Z","cooked":"<p>I also use <a href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/u/poppeseed">Poppeseed</a>’s approach.<br>
