<p>I can’t think of another solution this time</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-10-06T15:52:56.089Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":82,"readers_count":81,"score":16.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":506892,"topic_slug":"wpilib-units-part-2-unit-conversions-and-cancellations","display_username":"Raphael","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":70286,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3990 prog student"},"post_url":"/t/wpilib-units-part-2-unit-conversions-and-cancellations/506892/3","custom_user_title":"3990 prog student","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3756419,"name":"Eli Barnett","username":"Oblarg","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/oblarg/{size}/161674_2.png","created_at":"2025-10-06T17:33:05.470Z","cooked":"<p>If you really want dimensional analysis to work “correctly” for arbitrary algebra on composite quantities, you will unfortunately probably need to use a language other than Java.</p>
<p>WPIUnits does about as good a job as can be managed given the constraints of Java’s type system, but fundamentally, Java’s extremely weak nominal generics-by-erasure are just not up to the task of representing dimensional algebra.  You cannot expect it to work well for things like this - you may be able to find a call chain that technically compiles, but it is likely to be both verbose and inefficient at runtime.</p>
<p>If you want the “best available” dimensional analysis experience you should experiment with WPILibC, whose units of measure library “just works” for almost all cases (though the error messages when the compilation fails a dimensional coherence check can be…an experience).  The internal representation of units in WPILibC is mathematically primitive and thus is <em>guaranteed</em> to correctly and predictably resolve conversion chains like the one you’re encountering to code that is very nearly as efficient as if you had written it by hand.</p>
<p>If you don’t want to take the plunge to C++ (understandable), switching to Kotlin will probably help you out here, since the Kotlin compiler has an impressive array of hacks that expand the expressiveness of its type system beyond that of Java.  <a href="https://github.com/Kotlin-for-FRC/Botlin/tree/main" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Botlin</a> is a nice <span class="abbreviation">FRC<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="FIRST Robotics Competition"></template></span>-centered utility library that includes a more-powerful adaptation of WPIUnits, and can probably make your syntax here much more palatable (though it likely cannot do much about the runtime cost).</p>
<p>P.S. if you’re into rust, check out my library <a href="https://github.com/Oblarg/whippyunits" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">whippyunits</a>, which implements a (somewhat more powerful version of) WPILibC/WPIMath units.  Crate release coming soon™.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-10-06T17:36:11.831Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":11,"reads":63,"readers_count":62,"score":97.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":506892,"topic_slug":"wpilib-units-part-2-unit-conversions-and-cancellations","display_username":"Eli Barnett","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/Kotlin-for-FRC/Botlin/tree/main","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"GitHub - Kotlin-for-FRC/Botlin: Kotlin syntactical sugar for FRC","clicks":9},{"url":"https://github.com/Oblarg/whippyunits","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"GitHub - Oblarg/whippyunits: Pure rust units-of-measure library for applied numerical analysis","clicks":4}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":12381,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Robot apartments! invisible suburbs! skeleton treasuries!"},"post_url":"/t/wpilib-units-part-2-unit-conversions-and-cancellations/506892/4","custom_user_title":"Robot apartments! invisible suburbs! skeleton treasuries!","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":2}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":2,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"a